The Controlling Authority Retrieval (CAR) paper formalizes a framework for authority-governed knowledge retrieval that focuses on recovering the active frontier of the authority closure of a semantic anchor set. This framework addresses situations where a later document can formally void an earlier one, even if they are semantically distant. The two central results include Theorem 4, which provides necessary-and-sufficient conditions for a retrieved set to achieve total controlling authority (TCA) of 1, and Proposition 2, which establishes a worst-case ceiling for scope-indexed algorithms in this context.

